<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Related Party Activity
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	Investment in Crystal Financial SBIC LP
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	On March&nbsp;15, 2013, Crystal Financial committed $50,750,000 of capital to Crystal Financial SBIC LP (the &#147;Fund&#148;)
	in exchange for a 65.91% limited partner interest. Crystal Financial SBIC LP was established to operate as a small business investment company under the Small Business Investment Company (&#147;SBIC&#148;) Act. Of the total amount committed,
	$29,330,658 and $33,129,151 remained unfunded at December&nbsp;31, 2016 and December&nbsp;31, 2015, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Some of the managing members of the Fund&#146;s general partner, Crystal SBIC GP LLC (the &#147;General Partner&#148;), are
	also members of Crystal Financial&#146;s management team and, until July&nbsp;28, 2016 (see Note 5), held ownership interests in Crystal Financial LLC through their investments in Crystal Management LP. Crystal Financial and the General Partner have
	entered into a Services Agreement whereby Crystal Financial provides certain administrative services to the General Partner in exchange for a waiver of the quarterly management fee that it owes to the General Partner. Crystal Financial has also
	entered into a Loan Agreement with the Fund in order to meet short term capital needs. At December&nbsp;31, 2016 and December&nbsp;31, 2015, $620,000 and $11,204,000 remains outstanding on the Loan Agreement,
	respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Amounts outstanding on the Loan Agreement accrue interest at Prime plus 0.50%, unless such amount is less than 4.0%, in which case interest accrues at Libor plus 4.00%, up to a maximum of 5.00%. At
	December&nbsp;31, 2016, borrowings on the facility accrued interest at 4.25%. Crystal Financial earned interest income on this facility totaling $112,785 and $38,801 during 2016 and 2015, respectively. The Loan Agreement expires on June&nbsp;18,
	2017 and may be extended or renewed at the sole discretion of the Company.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company accounts for its limited partner
	interest in the Fund as an equity method investment in the accompanying consolidated financial statements (see Note 7). Crystal Financial contributed $3,798,493 to the Fund during 2016 and $3,295,283 to the Fund during 2015. Crystal Financial
	received cash distributions from the Fund totaling $3,861,325 and $1,188,999 during 2016 and 2015, respectively. In accordance with the equity method of accounting, the Company was allocated net income from the Fund totaling $4,269,660 and
	$3,564,720 for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016 and December&nbsp;31, 2015. These amounts represent the Company&#146;s allocation of the Fund&#146;s net income in accordance with the Fund&#146;s Limited Partnership Agreement. Crystal
	Financial&#146;s investment in the Fund is recorded as Investment in Crystal Financial SBIC LP in the accompanying consolidated balance sheets and its share of earnings and losses are recorded as Interest in earnings of equity method investee on the
	consolidated statements of operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	16
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage183"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	Crystal Financial LLC
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	Years Ended December&nbsp;31, 2016 and December&nbsp;31, 2015
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Crystal Management LP
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Crystal Management LP was formed on December&nbsp;9, 2013 under the laws of the state of Delaware. In accordance with the
	executed Limited Partnership Agreement, dated December&nbsp;31, 2013, the primary purpose of Crystal Management LP was to maintain the ownership interests of Crystal Financial employees. Through Crystal Management LP, these ownership interests are
	invested in the Company. Crystal Financial is the general partner of Crystal Management LP. Despite being the general partner, Crystal Financial held no economic interest in Crystal Management LP.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	On July&nbsp;28, 2016, Solar acquired all of Crystal Management LP&#146;s ownership interests in the Company (see Note 5).
	Accordingly, effective December&nbsp;19, 2016, Crystal Management LP was dissolved.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Member&#146;s Capital
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Crystal Financial has issued limited liability company interests, referred to as units. Each unit entitles its holder
	to one vote on all matters submitted to a vote of the members. The original purchase price of each unit as of the Acquisition Date was $1,000 per unit.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Certain of the individual employee&#146;s ownership units contained put options which, upon exercise, would require Crystal
	Financial to repurchase the outstanding units at their fair value, as defined in Crystal Financial&#146;s Operating Agreement, on the date of exercise. Holders redeemed 263 units during the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. The redemption value of
	the redeemable units, which also equals the fair value, as defined, totaled $5,270,115 at December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	There
	were 279,863 units outstanding at December&nbsp;31, 2015. Solar, through its investment in Crystal Capital Financial Holdings LLC, owned 275,000 units and Crystal Financial employees, through their investment in Crystal Management LP, owned the
	remaining 4,863 units, at December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With the payout of the 2013 long-term incentive
	plan (&#147;LTIP&#148;) bonus pool in March 2016 (see Note 6), Crystal Financial employees purchased an incremental 440 ownership units in the Company. The fair value of the units on the date of purchase totaled $463,708.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	On July&nbsp;28, 2016, Solar purchased Crystal Management LP&#146;s outstanding ownership interest in the Company for
	$5,736,973. Upon the closing of this transaction, Solar owns 100% of the outstanding equity interest in Crystal Financial. Crystal Capital Financial Holdings LLC was dissolved effective September&nbsp;30, 2016. At December&nbsp;31, 2016, the Company
	had 280,303 outstanding ownership units.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Commitments and Contingencies
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company is party to financial instruments with
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	off-balance
</FONT>
	sheet risk including
	unfunded revolver and delayed draw term loan commitments to certain borrowers. At December&nbsp;31, 2016, the Company also has an outstanding commitment to fund an $85,000,000 term loan on or before June&nbsp;30, 2017, subject to certain customary
	conditions. Subsequent to year end, the Company assigned a portion of its commitment to a third party lender and additionally, the borrower to which the commitment was granted, exercised its option to reduce the facility&#146;s outstanding
	commitment. Accordingly, the Company&#146;s commitment decreased to $37,500,000.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Under the revolving credit and delayed
	draw term loans, aggregate unfunded commitments including the $85,000,000 term loan commitment total $110,739,917 and $46,945,837 at December&nbsp;31, 2016 and December&nbsp;31, 2015. These agreements have fixed expiration dates. The revolving
	credit agreements typically
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	17
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage184"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	Crystal Financial LLC
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	Years Ended December&nbsp;31, 2016 and December&nbsp;31, 2015
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	require payment of a monthly fee equal to a certain percentage times the unused portion of the revolving line of credit. As the unfunded commitments may expire without being drawn upon, the total
	commitment amounts do not necessarily represent future cash requirements. The amount of credit that can be extended under each of the revolving credit agreements and delayed draw term loan agreements is typically limited to the borrower&#146;s
	available collateral, which is used in calculating the borrower&#146;s borrowing base at the time of a respective draw.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Effective January&nbsp;1, 2013, certain employees of Crystal Financial, including members of management, entered into a LTIP
	agreement. In accordance with the terms of the LTIP agreement, a bonus pool is calculated each calendar year, beginning with the amount calculated in 2014 with respect to results for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2013, and is based upon the
	achievement of certain operating results during the year. The bonus pool calculated and earned for each calendar year will be paid out two years after the year in which the bonus pool is calculated and earned. Accordingly, amounts relating to the
	year ended December&nbsp;31, 2013 were paid out in 2016. The calculated bonus pool is subject to a look-back calculation which could cause the amount that is ultimately paid out to be less than the amount originally calculated. Fifty percent of the
	bonus pool paid out during 2016 was paid in cash and the remaining was paid in fully-vested ownership units. Beginning with the bonus pool to be paid out in 2017, the amount will be paid entirely in cash with the expectation that 50% of the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	after-tax
</FONT>
	proceeds will be used to purchase shares of Solar stock in the open market.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Amounts recorded pursuant to the LTIP Agreement during the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016 and
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, are included as a component of accrued expenses on the accompanying consolidated balance sheets and as a component of compensation and benefits expense on the accompanying consolidated statements of operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Variable Interest Entity
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	On January&nbsp;1, 2016, the Company adopted ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	2015-02,
</FONT>
<I>
	Consolidation- Amendments
	to the
</I>
<I>
	Consolidation Analysis
</I>
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	(&#147;ASU-2015-02&#148;)
</FONT>
</FONT>
	which revised the existing consolidation guidance and required the Company to
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	re-evaluate
</FONT>
	its investments for the existence of variable interest entities. Under the consolidation guidance, the Company must evaluate (a)&nbsp;whether it holds a variable interest in an entity, (b)&nbsp;whether
	the entity is a variable interest entity (&#147;VIE&#148;) and (c)&nbsp;whether the Company is the primary beneficiary of the VIE. Prior to the adoption of ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	2015-02,
</FONT>
	it was determined that Crystal Financial
	SBIC LP was not a variable interest entity. This conclusion was based on the fact that (a)&nbsp;the partners, as a whole, have sufficient equity at risk to permit Crystal Financial SBIC LP to finance its activities and (b)&nbsp;the partners, as a
	whole, do not lack the power to direct the activities, the obligation to absorb expected losses, or the right to receive expected returns of Crystal Financial SBIC LP. Upon adoption of the new guidance, the granting of substantive
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	kick-out
</FONT>
	rights became a key consideration in determining whether a limited partnership is a VIE and whether or not that entity should be consolidated. As the Limited Partnership Agreement does not permit a simple
	majority of the limited partners of Crystal Financial SBIC LP to exercise
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	kick-out
</FONT>
	rights, these rights are deemed to not be substantive. Accordingly, Crystal Financial SBIC LP is deemed to be a VIE. In
	assessing whether or not Crystal Financial, together with its de facto agents, meet the criteria to consolidate the VIE, it was determined that substantially all of the VIE&#146;s activities are not conducted on behalf of Crystal Financial. As such,
	the Company&#146;s conclusion to not consolidate Crystal Financial SBIC LP did not change with the adoption of ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	2015-02.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	18
</P>

<TR STYLE = "PAGE-BREAK-INSIDE:AVOID">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(1)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	includes the equity investment the Company has made, or is required to make, and amounts outstanding under the
	Loan Agreement with Crystal Financial SBIC LP.
</P>
</TD>

</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Fair Value of Financial Instruments
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	ASC 820,
<I>
	Fair Value Measurements
</I>
	(&#147;ASC 820&#148;) establishes a three-level hierarchy for disclosure of
	fair value measurements. The valuation hierarchy is based upon the transparency of inputs to the valuation of an asset or liability as of the measurement date. The three levels are defined as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Level&nbsp;1-
</FONT>
	inputs to the valuation methodology are quoted prices (unadjusted) for
	identical assets or liabilities in active markets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Level&nbsp;2-
</FONT>
	inputs to the
	valuation methodology include quoted prices for similar assets and liabilities in active markets, and inputs that are observable for the asset or liability, either directly or indirectly, for substantially the full term of the financial instrument
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Level&nbsp;3-
</FONT>
	inputs to the valuation methodology are unobservable and significant
	to the fair value measurement.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	A financial instrument&#146;s categorization within the valuation
	hierarchy is based upon the lowest level of input that is significant to the fair value measurement.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following tables present recorded amounts of financial assets measured at fair value on a recurring basis as of
	December&nbsp;31, 2016 and December&nbsp;31, 2015. There were no financial liabilities at either December&nbsp;31, 2016 or December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<U>
	December&nbsp;31, 2016:
</U>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The fair values of the Company&#146;s derivative contracts are obtained from a third party and
	are subject to review and oversight by management. They were determined using widely accepted valuation techniques including discounted cash flow analysis based on the contractual terms of the derivatives, such as the period to maturity of each
	instrument.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;They use observable and unobservable market based inputs, including interest rate curves and implied volatilities. In addition, the Company considered both its own and its counterparty&#146;s risk of nonperformance
	in determining the fair value of its derivative financial instruments by estimating the current and potential future exposure under the derivative financial instruments that both the Company and the counterparty were at risk for as of the valuation
	date. The credit risk of the Company and its counterparty was factored into the calculation of the estimated fair value of the derivative contracts.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following tables present a summary of significant unobservable inputs and valuation techniques of the Company&#146;s
	Level&nbsp;3 fair value measurements at December&nbsp;31, 2016 and December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<U>
	December&nbsp;31, 2016
</U>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	There were no financial instruments classified as or transferred into or out of level 1 or 2
	in the fair value hierarchy during the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016 or December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company&#146;s
	financial instruments consist of cash, restricted cash, interest receivable, loans receivable, its investment in Crystal Financial SBIC LP, derivative instruments, collateral held for borrower obligations and the revolving credit facility. Due to
	the short-term nature of the Company&#146;s cash, restricted cash, interest receivable, and collateral held for borrower obligations, the carrying value approximates fair value.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company&#146;s loans receivable are recorded at outstanding principal, net of any deferred fees and costs and unamortized
	purchase discounts. If the Company elected the fair value option, the estimated fair value of the Company&#146;s loans receivable would be derived using among other things, a discounted cash flow methodology, that considers various factors including
	the type of loan and related collateral, current market yields for similar debt investments, estimated cash flows, as well as a discount rate that reflects the Company&#146;s assessment of risk inherent in the cash flow
	estimates.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	If the Company elected the fair value option, the estimated fair value of the
	Company&#146;s revolving credit facility at December&nbsp;31, 2016 and December&nbsp;31, 2015, would approximate the carrying value. The fair value is estimated based on consideration of current market interest rates for similar debt instruments.
	The following table presents the carrying amounts, estimated fair values, and placement in the fair value hierarchy of the Company&#146;s long-term financial instruments, at December&nbsp;31, 2016 and December&nbsp;31, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>

	9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Subsequent Events
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company has evaluated subsequent events through February&nbsp;13, 2017, the date which the financial statements were
	available to be issued. Other than those described in the preceding notes, no material subsequent events have occurred through this date.
</P>

	&nbsp;
